Perfect—this is where everything clicks. Let’s walk through a real microservice flow and see how these Kinds work together inside one Argo CD Application on Kubernetes.

🚀 End-to-End Flow: One Microservice (User Service)
🧱 Step 0: What we’re building

A simple user-service that:

Runs in Pods
Exposed internally + externally
Auto-scales
Monitored
📦 1. ConfigMap (Configuration)

Stores app configs (no hardcoding)

kind: ConfigMap
metadata:
  name: user-config
data:
  DB_HOST: mysql
  ENV: production

👉 Used by your app inside Pods

🔐 2. ServiceAccount (Identity)
kind: ServiceAccount
metadata:
  name: user-sa

👉 Controls what your app can access (RBAC)

⚙️ 3. Deployment (Main brain)
kind: Deployment
metadata:
  name: user-service
spec:
  replicas: 2
  template:
    spec:
      serviceAccountName: user-sa
      containers:
      - name: app
        image: user-service:v1

👉 This creates and manages Pods

📦 4. Pod (Actual running unit)

You don’t create Pods manually here—Deployment does it.

👉 Pods:

Run your container
Use ConfigMap
Use ServiceAccount
🌐 5. Service (Internal access)
kind: Service
metadata:
  name: user-service
spec:
  selector:
    app: user-service
  ports:
    - port: 80
      targetPort: 8080

👉 Provides:

Stable IP
Load balancing across Pods
🌍 6. Ingress (External access)
kind: Ingress
metadata:
  name: user-ingress
spec:
  rules:
  - host: user.myapp.com
    http:
      paths:
      - path: /

👉 Allows users to access:

https://user.myapp.com
📈 7. HorizontalPodAutoscaler (Scaling)
kind: HorizontalPodAutoscaler
metadata:
  name: user-hpa

👉 Automatically:

Increases Pods when traffic ↑
Decreases when traffic ↓
🛡️ 8. PodDisruptionBudget (Stability)
kind: PodDisruptionBudget

👉 Ensures:

Minimum Pods always running
Safe during updates/restarts
📊 9. ServiceMonitor (Monitoring)

From Prometheus

kind: ServiceMonitor

👉 Tells monitoring system:

“Track metrics of this service”
🔁 Full Flow (This is what matters)
User Request
     ↓
Ingress (entry point)
     ↓
Service (load balancer)
     ↓
Pods (running app)
     ↑
Deployment (manages Pods)
     ↑
ConfigMap + ServiceAccount (support)
🔄 Where Argo CD fits

Inside one Argo CD Application, all these YAMLs exist in Git:

repo/
 ├── deployment.yaml
 ├── service.yaml
 ├── ingress.yaml
 ├── configmap.yaml
 ├── hpa.yaml

👉 Argo CD:

Reads Git
Applies all these Kinds
Keeps them in sync
🧠 Big Picture (VERY IMPORTANT)

👉 Your microservice = combination of multiple Kinds

NOT just Deployment.

🔥 Real-world upgrade (what companies do)

They also add:

API Gateway configs (KongIngress, KongPlugin)
Alerts (PrometheusRule)
Security scans (BackgroundScanReport)
🎯 Interview-ready summary

👉
“A microservice in Kubernetes is composed of multiple resource types like Deployment, Service, Ingress, ConfigMap, and HPA, all working together to run, expose, scale, and manage the application, and Argo CD manages these resources declaratively from Git.”












